        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our science goals require detecting 10% variations in the azimuthal distribution of flux in the debris ring of HD 181327 at 5 sigma (resolving the 0.4" radial FWHM of the ring is uneccessary).  We expect azimuthal variations to be ~0.5 - 1.5" in size.  The total flux of the HD 181327 disk at 1.3 mm is ~8 mJy, estimated by interpolating between the 870 micron LABOCA APEX measurement of 52 mJy and the 3.2 mm ATCA measurement of 0.7 mJy.  Given a disk diameter of 3.5", we expect a peak continuum flux density per beam of 0.52 mJy with 0.6" resolution, requiring a sensitivity of 0.01 mJy to achieve the science goals.  This resolution is small enough to avoid beam dilution, but large enough to provide adequate sensitivity to the variations with a total integration time of 2.9 hours.  The largest size scale expected is ~few arcseconds, obviating the need for ACA or multiple configurations.

Our proposed observations combine continuum imaging with CO emission line detection, so we choose band 6 to observe the CO 2-1 transition. We propose to set up the correlator with 3 out of 4 bands as continuum with maximum bandwidth, and one band straddling the CO line with resolution adequate to detect asymmetric CO emission on a Keplerian orbit.  The Keplerian orbital speed near the parent ring is 3.5 km/s.  Given the disk inclination of 28.5 degrees from face-on the projected CO linewidth is 3.5 km/s.  We therefore request 0.6 km/s resolution for the band used for CO observations.  Including a higher-resolution CO band to search for serendipitous detection results in only 7% loss of sensitivity in the continuum bands, and therefore has a negligible effect on our time request. Because we are searching for CO emission serendipitously, the peak line flux per beam is unknown and we simply estimate it from the RMS noise expected for the line.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
